{
  "text": "The ray tracing process is designed to generate the characteristic lines and obtain the related characteristic information of the geometry. In common sense, the ray tracers rely on mathematical solutions for the ray intersection an object and require different routines to be programed for various types of geometrical objects. Thus, the geometry-dependence of ray tracers was another key Fig. 2 . The lattice geometry model visualized in MCAM problem which prevents some MOC codes from broader use to some extent. With the rapid development of computer graphics, the first generalized ray tracer was developed in ANEMONA [CITATION_1] which was based on the theory of R-functions. A generalized ray tracer which is geometry-independent does not need to recognize the specific geometry objects.",
